<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Hooking Strategy With CK Words</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">S-hook at the end:</span> Most CK words take an S — BACKS, DECKS, KICKS, RACKS. This lets you score your word while creating a parallel play with the S.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">ED/ING extensions:</span> Many CK words extend with -ED (BACKED, KICKED, RACKED) or -ING (BACKING, KICKING). Keep these in mind when you draw common suffixes.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Front hooks:</span> Add letters to the front — ACK → BACK, HACK, JACK, LACK, PACK, RACK, TACK. One root word, 7+ derivatives.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
  <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Key Insight</p>
  <p class="text-base text-gray-200">CK words rarely appear at the start of words — they almost always end a syllable. This means CK plays are excellent defensive moves since opponents cannot easily extend them forward.</p>
